<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> LONDON (Reuters) - Leaders of the Fire Brigades Union (FBU) are due to meet later today to decide whether to provide emergency cover during planned nationwide strikes this winter. <br>
The meeting follows calls from the government for firefighters to respond to emergency 999 calls during their scheduled walkouts, the first in 25 years. <br>
<br>
A voluntary code drawn up in 1979 by the Trades Union Congress says industrial action should avoid endangering the public. <br>
<br>
&quot;The government now have six days to settle this dispute before any lives are put at risk,&quot; FBU general secretary Andy Gilchrist said in a statement released before the meeting on Wednesday. The first, 48-hour walkout begins on October 29. <br>
<br>
A planned meeting between union leaders and MPs at the House of Commons was cancelled. <br>
<br>
The FBU announced on Monday it would hold six nationwide strikes from late October through to December unless the government agreed to a 40 percent pay rise. <br>
<br>
Armed forces have begun training to replace the firefighters, using Cold War-era fire engines known as &quot;Green Goddesses&quot;. <br>
<br>
Fears are growing that the strike may snowball, leading to walkouts among a wide range of public sector workers. <br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
What do you think?<br>
Extortion or do they deserve it?<br>
